The Annotated Score Function Estimator¶

Yao Fu, Columbia University | yao.fu@columbia.edu | Mon Mar 03rd 2020

The gumbel estimator is an increasingly popular estimator for the gradients over discrete samples. In this notebook, we insvestigate this estimator from an engineering perspective, and reveal all the coding details of them.

A VAE model with categorical latent $z$ for mnist digits¶

As a baseline, we implement a VAE model for the mnist digits, where the encoder/ inference network $q_\phi(z|x)$ and the decoder $p_\theta(x | x)$ are both MLPs. We use a categorical distribution with 10 class to model $q_\phi(z | x)$. The categorical nature induces non-differentiability, which is tackled by the score function estimator.

The score function estimator¶

We denote the gradient of the inference network in the ELBO objective estimated by the score function estimator as:

$$\nabla_\phi [\lambda \cdot \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi(z|x)}[\log p_\theta(x|z)] + \beta \cdot \mathcal{H}(q_\phi(z|x))] = \\ \lambda \cdot \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi(z|x)}[(\log p_\theta(x | z) - b(x)) \nabla_\phi \log q_\phi(z|x)] + \beta \cdot \nabla_\phi\mathcal{H}(q_\phi(z|x)) $$

In our implementation, $\beta$ is denoted as beta_z, $\lambda$ is denoted as lambd_z

Speciafically, we discuss

  • Implementation of the score function estimator
  • Training process
  • Tuning lambda
  • Tuning beta
  • lambda and beta are coupled
  • Variance of the gradients
  • Conclusion

This notebook is, of course, inspired by Sasha Sush's The Annotated Transformer: https://nlp.seas.harvard.edu/2018/04/03/attention.html

Implementation of the score function estimator¶

The major part is implemented in the forward_score_fn function

The objective log_p_x

  • This is the ultimate objective that we want to maximize
  • In our implementation, we use log_p_x = -F.binary_cross_entropy(x_out, x_target).
  • Typically in a vanilla VAE, one would use -log_p_x = F.binary_cross_entropy(x_out, x_target) and minimize it
  • We use a negation here because we will need it in the score function estimator

The score function estimator

  • is implemented by loss_z = lambd_z * (log_p_x - b).detach() * log_prob_z
  • We use detach because we only need to differentiate over the log probability of z. Be careful here!
  • Note that this formula is specifically for maximizing log_p_x, and can NOT be used for minimizing -log_p_x (because then symbol of the baseline would be positive)
  • Of course we could instead derive a minimization formula for -log_p_x, but here we follow the convension of the literature
  • loss_z would be the actual loss for the encoder, however, during training, unlike log_p_x, it does NOT monotonically increase or decrease, as we will demonstrate

KL divergence between q(z|x) and a uniform prior

  • is implemented as the entropy of of q(z|x) as the two are same
  • From this perspective, the regularization from a uniform prior can also be viewed as the entropy regularization. It is crutial for a reparameterized estimator.

The final loss loss = -(log_p_x.mean() + loss_z.mean()) - self.beta_z * ent_z

  • In this equation we negate log_p_x and loss_z because torch is doing minimization
In [136]:
class CategoricalVAE(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, num_class, num_sample, beta_z, lambd_z):
    super(CategoricalVAE, self).__init__()
    
    self.num_sample = num_sample
    self.beta_z = beta_z
    self.lambd_z = lambd_z

    self.fc1 = nn.Linear(784, 400)
    self.fc2 = nn.Linear(400, num_class)
    self.fc3 = nn.Linear(num_class, 400)
    self.fc4 = nn.Linear(400, 784)
    return

  def encode(self, x):
    h1 = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
    logits = self.fc2(h1)
    q_prob = F.softmax(logits, dim=-1)
    log_q_prob = torch.log(q_prob + 1e-10)
    return q_prob, log_q_prob

  def decode(self, z):
    h3 = F.relu(self.fc3(z))
    return torch.sigmoid(self.fc4(h3))
  
  def sample_hard(self, log_q, num_sample):
    batch_size = log_q.size(0)
    num_class = log_q.size(1)
    
    log_q = log_q.view(batch_size, 1, num_class).repeat(1, num_sample, 1)
    m = OneHotCategorical(logits=log_q)
    z_sample = m.sample() # [batch, sample, class]
    log_prob_z = m.log_prob(z_sample) # [batch, sample]
    return z_sample, log_prob_z
  
  def baseline(self, reward):
    num_sample = reward.size(1)
    if(num_sample == 1): return 0
    b = reward.sum(dim=1, keepdim=True)
    b = (b - reward) / (num_sample - 1)
    return b

  def forward_score_fn(self, x):
    batch_size = x.size(0)
    q_prob, log_q_prob = self.encode(x)
    ent_z = -(q_prob * log_q_prob).sum(dim=1).mean()
    
    z_sample, log_prob_z = self.sample_hard(log_q_prob, self.num_sample)
    x_out = self.decode(z_sample) # [batch, sample, 784]
    x_target = x.view(batch_size, 1, 784).repeat(1, self.num_sample, 1) # [batch, sample, 784]
    log_p_x = -F.binary_cross_entropy(x_out, x_target, reduction='none') # [batch, sample, 784]
    log_p_x = log_p_x.mean(dim=-1) # [batch, sample]
    
    log_p_x_ = log_p_x.detach()
    b = self.baseline(log_p_x_)
    loss_z = self.lambd_z * (log_p_x_ - b) * log_prob_z
    
    loss = -(log_p_x.mean() + loss_z.mean()) - self.beta_z * ent_z
    return loss, log_p_x.mean(), loss_z.mean(), ent_z, z_sample

Implementation of the training loops¶

During training, we inspect the model at every print_interval = 2000 steps, and visualize the model output for each z_i at the end

In [95]:
def visualize(config, model):
  z = np.eye(config['num_class'])
  x = model.decode(torch.from_numpy(z).type(torch.float))
  x = x.view(config['num_class'], 28, 28).detach().numpy()
  
  if(config['num_class'] > 10):
    img_0 = np.hstack([x[i] for i in range(int(config['num_class'] / 2))])
    img_1 = np.hstack([x[i] for i in range(int(config['num_class'] / 2), config['num_class'])])
    img = np.vstack([img_0, img_1])
  else:
    img = np.hstack([x[i] for i in range(config['num_class'])])
  plt.imshow(img)
  plt.show()
  return

def print_at(i, num_iter, print_interval=2000):
  if(i % print_interval == 0): return True
  elif(i == num_iter - 1): return True
  return False

def report_grad(model):
    """Report the average norm the gradient, used for monitoring training"""
    print('gradient of the model parameters:')

    grad_norms = {}
    grad_std = {}
    for name, param in model.named_parameters():
      frist_level_name = name.split('.')[0]
      if(param.requires_grad and param.grad is not None):
        # print(name, param.grad.norm(), param.grad.std())
        if(frist_level_name in grad_norms):
          grad_norms[frist_level_name].append(
            param.grad.norm().detach().cpu().numpy())
          grad_std[frist_level_name].append(
            param.grad.std().detach().cpu().numpy())
        else: 
          grad_norms[frist_level_name] = [
            param.grad.norm().detach().cpu().numpy()]
          grad_std[frist_level_name] = [
            param.grad.std().detach().cpu().numpy()]
    
    for frist_level_name in grad_norms:
      print(frist_level_name, 
        np.average(grad_norms[frist_level_name]),
        np.std(grad_std[frist_level_name]))
    return 

def train_score_fn(config, print_log=True):
  model = CategoricalVAE(config['num_class'], config['num_sample'], config['beta_z'], config['lambd_z'])
  params = list(model.parameters())
  opt = Adam(params, 1e-3)

  batch_size = 50

  log_p_x_log = []
  loss_z_log = []
  ent_z_log = []
  
  if('print_interval' in config): print_interval = config['print_interval']
  else: print_interval = 2000

  for i in range(config['num_iter']):
    x, y = mnist.train.next_batch(batch_size)

    model.zero_grad()
    loss, log_p_x, loss_z, ent_z, z = model.forward_score_fn(torch.from_numpy(x))
    loss.backward()
    opt.step()

    log_p_x = float(log_p_x.detach().cpu().numpy())
    ent_z = float(ent_z.detach().cpu().numpy())
    loss_z = float(loss_z.detach().cpu().numpy())
    log_p_x_log.append(log_p_x)
    loss_z_log.append(loss_z)
    ent_z_log.append(ent_z)

    if(print_at(i, config['num_iter'], print_interval)):
      if(print_log):
        loss = loss.detach().cpu().numpy()
        z = z.detach().numpy()
        print('step %d, log_p_x %.4g, loss_z %.4g, ent_z %.4g' % (i, log_p_x, loss_z, ent_z))
        z_ind = z[:3].argmax(-1)
        print('sampled z index are:', z_ind[0], z_ind[1], z_ind[2])
        report_grad(model)
      else: print('.')

  print('finished!')
  
  visualize(config, model)
  return model, np.array(log_p_x_log), np.array(loss_z_log), np.array(ent_z_log)

Training process¶

Below is the standard architecture we will use through this post. we call it the base model in our experiments. In the later part we will compare different hyper-parameter settings with this setting

During training, we monitor

  • log_p_x: the optimization objective
  • loss_z: the auxilary loss of z, although we seem to be maximizing it, it is not actually monotonically increasing
  • ent_z: the entropy of z
  • gradient of the model parameters, we will further investigate it in the variance reduction section

Tuning lambd_z¶

lambd_z controls the scale of the inference network q. Alternatively, we can use seperate optimizers for q and p, and use different learning rate. Since we use the same optimizer here, we use the coefficient lambd_z. The goal is to make the norm of the two networks sensible

The behavior is interesting as we can see that the model took a while to find out a sensible convergence.

The training curve shows that in the begining of training, due to a larger lambd_z, the model did not find a meaningful loss_z, and it is close to 0, leading to non-informative gradient. After about 1200 steps, the model gets lucky and start to converge again. But it converges to a worse local as we see a worse sample quality.

Note that runing the above setting with a different random seed may lead to different behaviors.

As we can see, setting lambd_z to 0.1 leads to:

  • a meaningless uniform posterior (regardless of the input), and consequently
  • the close-to 2.3 entropy (compared to 0.27+ in the base model)
  • the suboptimal reconstruction loss (log_p_x = -0.26, campared to -0.21 in the base model)
  • he vanished gradient of the encoder (grad at level of 1e-5, compared to 1e-3 in the base model)
  • and the meaningless decoder output

The answer is no. As we can see, setting beta_z to 0 would lead to:

  • a meaningless concentrated posterior (concentrated on z=5 no matter the input), and consequently
  • the close-to 0 entropy (compared to 0.30+ in the base model)
  • the vanished gradient of the encoder (grad at level of 1e-16, compared to 1e-3 in the base model)
  • the suboptimal reconstruction loss (log_p_x = -0.27, campared to -0.21 when in the base model)
  • and the meaningless decoder output

The answer is still no. As we can see, setting beta_z to 0.1 would lead to

  • a meaningless uniform posterior (a uniform distribution with 10 class has entropy 2.3)
  • the vanished gradient of the encoder (grad at level of 1e-5, compared to 1e-3 in the base model)
  • the suboptimal reconstruction loss (log_p_x = -0.26, campared to -0.21 when in the base model)
  • and the meaningless decoder output

lambda and beta are coupled¶

The observation from the previous experiments gives us the insight that:

  • when beta_z is small, the loss_z is weak, then the encoder would be overwhelmed by ent_z, leading to a meaningless uniform posterior
  • when beta_z is large, the loss_z is strong, then the encoder would be overwhelmed by loss_z, leading to a meaningless concentrated posterior

This indicates that the scale of beta_z and lambd_z should be paired. Specifically we show that holding other parameters fixed, the following (beta_z, lambd_z) pairs are effective:

  • (0.1, 10)
  • (0.01, 1.0) - our base model
  • (0.001, 0.1)

Below we show the experiments on (beta_z = 0.1, lambd_z = 10)

Here we compare the generation quality between models with/ without variance reduction

In [142]:
def compare_model_outputs(model_0, model_1, config):
  z = np.eye(config['num_class'])
  x_0 = model_0.decode(torch.from_numpy(z).type(torch.float))
  x_0 = x_0.view(config['num_class'], 28, 28).detach().numpy()
  
  z = np.eye(config['num_class'])
  x_1 = model_1.decode(torch.from_numpy(z).type(torch.float))
  x_1 = x_1.view(config['num_class'], 28, 28).detach().numpy()
  
  img_0 = np.hstack([x_0[i] for i in range(int(config['num_class']))])
#   img_1 = np.hstack([x_0[i] for i in range(int(config['num_class'] / 2), config['num_class'])])
  img_x = np.zeros_like(img_0)
  img_2 = np.hstack([x_1[i] for i in range(int(config['num_class']))])
#   img_3 = np.hstack([x_1[i] for i in range(int(config['num_class'] / 2), config['num_class'])])
  
  img = np.vstack([img_0, img_x, img_2])
  plt.imshow(img)
  plt.show()
  return

In [134]:
def compare_training_curve(curve_0, curve_1):
  f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, sharey=True)
  f.set_size_inches(8, 2, forward=True)
  x = np.arange(len(curve_0))
  ax1.plot(x, curve_0)
  ax2.plot(x, curve_1)
  plt.show()
  return

Conclusion¶

In this post, we discuss the engineering details of the score function estimator.

  • We first give an implementation of the estimator, highlighting the symbols of the loss terms, and that we need to detach the reward for unbiasedness.
  • Then we show that the two parameters lambd_z and beta_z are coupled. One should tune them carefully to find the right pair.
  • Finally we visualize the nessecity of variance reduction and show how it improves training.
